title: Prevent inflator from mutating circuitJson reference and breaking the cache
description: Fixes bug where inflator mutates circuitJson reference, causing incorrect data and layout errors in components using shared circuitJson.
body:
This pull request addresses a bug where the subcircuit inflator was mutating the
circuitJson object reference, causing issues with caching and component reuse.  

Problem                                                                         

When the same circuitJson object was used for multiple components, such as two  
`<board>`s in a `<panel>`, the inflator for the first component would modify the    
shared circuitJson. This resulted in subsequent components receiving            
already-transformed and incorrect data, leading to layout errors and breaking   
rendering caches.                                                               

The primary issue was in inflatePcbComponent, which applied transformations     
directly to the circuitJson array.                                              

Solution                                                                        

The inflatePcbComponent function now performs a deep copy of the relevant       
circuit elements before applying transformations. This ensures that the original
circuitJson object remains untouched, preserving its integrity for reuse.       

Code Change:                                                                    

  In                                                                           
   lib/components/primitive-components/Group/Subcircuit/inflators/inflatePcbComp
   onent.ts, the relativeElements are now cloned using                          
   JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(...)) before transformation.                       

Related Changes                                                                 

  The Board component logic has been improved to correctly handle initial      
   dimensions provided via circuitJson.                                         
  A new test case and fixture (simple-circuit.json) have been added to verify  
   the fix with multiple boards using the same circuitJson in a panel.

title: Correctly inflate traces and groups from circuitJson
description: Fixes bug in subcircuit inflation logic where nested groups and trace paths were not handled correctly, leading to incorrect connections within circuitJson.
body:
This pull request addresses a bug in the subcircuit inflation logic where nested
groups and the associated trace paths within a circuitJson were not being       
handled correctly.                                                              

Previously, when inflating a subcircuit, all groups from the circuitJson were   
added as direct children to the new subcircuit, ignoring any nested structure.  
This resulted in incorrect selector paths for traces, causing them to fail to   
connect components within those nested groups.                                  

The following changes have been made to resolve this issue:                     

  inflateSourceGroup.ts: The group inflator now correctly respects the         
   parent_source_group_id property, ensuring that groups are added to their     
   proper parent within the hierarchy.                                          
  inflateSourceTrace.ts: The getSelectorPath utility has been updated to       
   correctly traverse the nested group structure, allowing it to generate valid 
   selector paths for traces.                                                   
  SubcircuitI.ts: Added source_group_id to the interface to support the        
   improved path resolution logic.                                              
  A new test case (subcircuit-circuit-json09) has been added to validate that a
   subcircuit with nested groups and traces can be inflated correctly.

title: feat: Enable circuitJson on boards and panelization
description: Enables the use of circuitJson directly on Board components and adds a new PanelLayout render phase for panelizing these boards.
body:
This PR introduces the ability to use `circuitJson` directly on `Board` components, making it possible to define board layouts using circuit JSON. Additionally, it adds a new `PanelLayout` render phase to correctly handle the panelization of these new `circuitJson`-defined boards.

**Key Changes:**

- **`Board` now supports `circuitJson`:** The `Board` component can now directly accept a `circuitJson` prop to define its internal components and traces.
- **New `PanelLayout` render phase:** A dedicated render phase has been added to manage the layout and positioning of boards within a `Panel`, specifically for those defined by `circuitJson`.
- **Refactored `inflateCircuitJson`:** The logic for inflating `circuitJson` has been extracted into a shared utility function, `inflateCircuitJson`, which is now used by both `Subcircuit` and `Board` components.
- **Introduced `SubcircuitContext`:** A new interface, `SubcircuitContext`, was created to generalize components that can act as a context for subcircuits.
- **Panel layout logic moved:** The panel-specific layout logic has been moved from `doInitialPcbComponentAnchorAlignment` to a new `doInitialPanelLayout` method within the `Panel` component.
- **New test cases:** Added comprehensive test cases for panelizing boards defined with `circuitJson`, including explicit positioning.

title: Add error detection flow that validates node module imports progressively
description: Adds a validation flow for node module imports that checks for package declaration in package.json, existence of files in node_modules, unsupported TypeScript entrypoints, and empty dist directories.
body:
## Changes

### New Errors (5 sequential validation steps)

1. **"Node module imported but not in package.json"**
   - Checks if package is declared in dependencies/devDependencies/peerDependencies
   - Thrown early to prevent fallback attempts for undeclared packages

2. **"Node module has no files in the node_modules directory"**
   - Verifies node_modules directory exists with actual files
   - Only enforced when CDN fallback is unavailable

3. **"Node module has a typescript entrypoint that is unsupported"**
   - Detects if main entry points to .ts/.tsx files
   - TypeScript source files require compilation before use

4. **"Node module has no files in dist, did you forget to transpile?"**
   - Verifies dist directory exists when main points to dist/
   - Helpful error for packages with build output in dist

5. **"Package is not declared in package.json"** (jsDelivr fallback)
   - Validates transitive dependencies from jsDelivr don't bypass package.json

### Validation Flow

```
Import Request
    
[STEP 1] Check package.json declaration
     NOT FOUND   Error: "Node module imported but not in package.json"
     FOUND 
[STEP 2] Check node_modules directory
     NO FILES   Error: "Node module has no files in the node_modules directory"
                  (or allow jsDelivr fallback if CDN enabled)
     EXISTS 
[STEP 3] Check main entrypoint
     IS .TS/.TSX   Error: "Node module has a typescript entrypoint that is unsupported"
     IS JS 
[STEP 4] Check dist directory (if main  dist/)
     EMPTY   Error: "Node module has no files in dist, did you forget to transpile?"
     HAS FILES 
 Import module

jsDelivr Fallback Path:
    [STEP 5] Check package.json declaration
     NOT FOUND   Error: "Package is not declared in package.json"
     FOUND   Fetch from CDN
```

description: How GapFillSubSolver Works GapFillSubSolver operates as a post-processing cleanup algorithm that creates brand new rectangles to fill empty spaces left after the main RectDiff placement. It follows a four-stage process: 1. SCAN: Detects uncovered areas using grid-based sweep-line algorithm, merging adjacent empty cells into maximal gap rectangles 2. body:
## How GapFillSubSolver Works

GapFillSubSolver operates as a post-processing cleanup algorithm that creates **brand new rectangles** to fill empty spaces left after the main RectDiff placement. It follows a four-stage process:

1. **SCAN**: Detects uncovered areas using grid-based sweep-line algorithm, merging adjacent empty cells into maximal gap rectangles
2. **SELECT**: Prioritizes gaps by size and multi-layer coverage, choosing the most valuable gap to fill next
3. **EXPAND**: Places seed point at gap center and grows a rectangle outward until hitting existing rectangles, obstacles, or boundaries
4. **PLACE**: Adds the successfully expanded rectangle to the solution as a new placement

## Fundamental Difference from RectDiff

**RectDiff** solves the **routing problem** - it places rectangles to enable electrical signal connections based on circuit topology and routing requirements from SimpleRouteJson input.

**GapFillSubSolver** solves the **coverage problem** - it maximizes board area utilization by filling leftover empty spaces with new rectangles, regardless of routing needs.

**RectDiff** creates rectangles for **electrical functionality** (routing paths), while **GapFillSubSolver** creates rectangles for **geometric efficiency** (space utilization). They serve complementary but entirely different purposes in the placement pipeline: connectivity versus coverage optimization.

title: refactor: migrate shape and path utilities to options-based parameter signatures
description: Refactors shape and path utility functions to use options-based parameter signatures for improved readability and consistency across the codebase.
body:
## Summary

This PR modernizes and unifies the function signatures across helper modules by converting multiple positional parameters into a single **options object**. This refactor improves readability, extensibility, and consistency across the codebase without altering existing functionality.

## Whats Changed

### **Refactored helper functions to use an options-object parameter**

The following functions now accept a single, typed options object instead of multiple positional arguments:

* `createCirclePath` in **circleShape.ts**
* `createOvalPath` in **ovalShape.ts**
* `createPillPath` in **pillShape.ts**
* `createPolygonPathFromOutline` in **polygonShape.ts**
* `createRoundedRectPath` in **roundedRectShape.ts**
* `createPointAdder` in **pathPointUtils.ts**

### **Additional updates**

* Updated all call sites across the codebase to use the new object-based parameters.
* Added dedicated TypeScript interfaces for each options object.
* Maintained backward compatibilityno change in runtime behavior.
* Improved internal consistency across shape/path helper utilities.

## Why This Matters

* **More readable code:** Named fields make calls clearer and self-documenting.
* **Easier extensibility:** New parameters can be added without introducing breaking changes.
* **Consistent API surface:** All helper functions follow a unified pattern.
* **Better DX:** TypeScript autocompletion and inline documentation now work more effectively.

## Testing

* All existing test suites pass without modifications.
* Manual verification completed across multiple real-world scenarios.
* Confirmed all call sites were correctly migrated.

---
